('general', 'edi-transactions', 'What is EDI in medical billing?',
'EDI (Electronic Data Interchange) is standardized electronic exchange of healthcare transactions between providers and payers: DEFINITION AND PURPOSE - Structured computer-to-computer exchange of business documents, replaces paper processes (paper claims, paper EOBs, phone calls), uses HIPAA-mandated standard formats (not custom formats), automated transmission and processing, secure encrypted exchange, reduces errors and processing time. Benefit: transforms manual paper-based billing to electronic automation. HIPAA EDI STANDARD TRANSACTIONS - Healthcare industry uses ANSI ASC X12 EDI standards, HIPAA Administrative Simplification mandates specific transactions, covered entities must accept EDI (payers required, providers encouraged). Key healthcare EDI transactions: (1) 837 - Healthcare Claim, (2) 835 - Healthcare Payment/Remittance, (3) 270 - Eligibility Inquiry, (4) 271 - Eligibility Response, (5) 276 - Claim Status Inquiry, (6) 277 - Claim Status Response, (7) 278 - Prior Authorization, (8) 997/999 - Functional Acknowledgment, (9) 834 - Benefit Enrollment, (10) 820 - Premium Payment. MOST COMMON TRANSACTIONS IN PRACTICE BILLING - (1) 837 CLAIM TRANSACTION - Electronic version of CMS-1500 or UB-04 paper claim, three types: 837P (professional/physician claims), 837I (institutional/hospital claims), 837D (dental claims), contains all claim information: patient demographics, insurance information, provider details, diagnosis codes (ICD-10), procedure codes (CPT/HCPCS), charges and dates. Replaces: mailing paper claims. (2) 835 REMITTANCE ADVICE - Electronic explanation of payment, shows: amounts paid, adjustments and reasons, denied claims with reason codes, patient responsibility, check/EFT payment details, claim-level and service-line level detail. Replaces: paper EOB (Explanation of Benefits). (3) 270/271 ELIGIBILITY - 270 inquiry request: patient coverage status, benefits information, copay/deductible amounts. 271 response from payer: coverage active/inactive, benefit details, authorization requirements. Replaces: phone calls to verify insurance. (4) 276/277 CLAIM STATUS - 276 inquiry: where is my claim?, 277 response: claim received, in process, paid, denied, specific status information. Replaces: phone calls for claim status. (5) 997/999 FUNCTIONAL ACKNOWLEDGMENT - Confirms receipt of EDI transaction, validates transaction structure (not claim adjudication), identifies syntax errors, provides tracking number. Technical confirmation only. HOW EDI WORKS IN BILLING - (1) Provider generates EDI transaction in billing system/EHR (e.g., 837 claim), (2) Transaction transmitted to clearinghouse or directly to payer (encrypted secure connection, SFTP/AS2/API), (3) Clearinghouse validates and routes to payer (or payer receives directly), (4) Payer receives, sends 997 acknowledgment, (5) Payer processes transaction, (6) Payer sends response transaction (835 payment, 271 eligibility response, 277 status), (7) Response received by provider system automatically, (8) System processes response (auto-post payments, update eligibility, display status). EDI ADVANTAGES OVER PAPER - Speed: electronic transmission seconds/minutes vs days for mail, claims processed 7-14 days faster, real-time eligibility vs 10-15 minute phone calls. Accuracy: standardized format reduces errors, automated validation catches issues, clean claim rates 95%+ vs 70-80% paper, reduces rejections by 50-70%. Efficiency: automated transmission (no printing/mailing/faxing), automated posting (ERA vs manual from paper), 70-80% staff time reduction, processes 100s of claims in minutes. Cost: postage eliminated ($0.55 per claim saved), reduced staff time, faster payment improves cash flow, lower cost per transaction. Tracking: complete audit trail, status updates automatic, no lost claims, real-time visibility. Security: encrypted transmission, no mail loss/theft, HIPAA compliant, audit logs. EDI REQUIREMENTS - Trading partner agreement with payer or clearinghouse, EDI enrollment with payers, billing system/EHR capable of generating EDI, secure transmission method (internet connection, SFTP/VPN), staff training on EDI workflows. EDI ENROLLMENT PROCESS - Complete trading partner agreement forms, provide practice/provider information (NPI, tax ID, demographics, contact information), specify transaction types (837, 835, 270/271, 276/277), provide technical connection details, testing period (submit test transactions, verify receipt and processing, validate response transactions), production go-live after successful testing. Timeline: 15-45 days typical depending on payer. CLEARINGHOUSE ROLE IN EDI - Maintains EDI connections to thousands of payers, single EDI connection for provider reaches all payers, translates to payer-specific EDI formats, validates EDI transactions before payer submission, manages technical complexity, handles payer enrollment coordination. Value: one EDI connection vs hundreds. HIPAA COMPLIANCE - Covered entities must: accept standard EDI transactions (payers required), use HIPAA standard versions and formats, implement administrative simplification, business associate agreements for EDI partners. Providers: encouraged but not mandated to send EDI (except Medicaid in some states), most choose EDI for efficiency. EDI VS TRADITIONAL - Paper claim: print, mail, 7-14 days to receive, manual data entry at payer, process 30-45 days. EDI claim: electronic transmission, seconds to receive, automated processing, process 14-30 days. Phone eligibility: 10-15 minute call, limited information, manual documentation. EDI eligibility: 10-30 second response, comprehensive data, auto-updates system. Paper EOB: mailed, manual posting, 1-2 hours per 100 claims. ERA (EDI 835): electronic, auto-posting, 10-15 minutes per 100 claims.',
'EDI (Electronic Data Interchange) = standardized electronic exchange of healthcare transactions replacing paper. Key transactions: 837 (claims, replaces CMS-1500), 835 (payment/remittance, replaces paper EOB), 270/271 (eligibility, replaces phone calls), 276/277 (claim status), 997/999 (acknowledgment). Process: generate in EHR → transmit to clearinghouse/payer → validate → process → response. Advantages: speed (seconds vs days), accuracy (95%+ clean claims vs 70-80% paper), efficiency (70-80% time savings), cost (no postage), tracking, security. Requirements: trading partner agreement, enrollment, EDI-capable system. Clearinghouse enables single connection to all payers.',
