('general', 'edi-transactions', 'What are the different EDI transaction types?',
'Healthcare uses standardized ANSI X12 EDI transaction sets for different business functions: CLAIM TRANSACTIONS - (1) 837 - HEALTHCARE CLAIM (most important) - Electronic submission of healthcare claims, three subtypes: 837P (professional claims from physicians/providers), 837I (institutional claims from hospitals/facilities), 837D (dental claims), contains: patient demographics and insurance, provider and billing information, diagnosis codes (ICD-10), procedure codes (CPT/HCPCS), service dates and charges, supporting documentation references. Purpose: request payment for services. Replaces: CMS-1500 paper form (professional), UB-04 paper form (institutional). Frequency: daily or real-time. PAYMENT TRANSACTIONS - (2) 835 - HEALTHCARE CLAIM PAYMENT/REMITTANCE ADVICE - Electronic payment and explanation information, details: payment amounts by claim and service line, adjustment codes and amounts (contractual, sequestration, etc.), reason codes (CARC - Claim Adjustment Reason Codes), remark codes (RARC - Remittance Advice Remark Codes), denied services with denial reasons, patient responsibility amounts, check number or EFT trace number, payment date. Purpose: explain payment and adjustments. Replaces: paper EOB/remittance. Enables: automatic payment posting (ERA). Frequency: typically weekly or per payment batch. ELIGIBILITY TRANSACTIONS - (3) 270 - ELIGIBILITY, COVERAGE, OR BENEFIT INQUIRY - Request for patient insurance information, includes: patient identifying information (name, DOB, member ID), provider information (NPI), inquiry type (general eligibility, specific service coverage), date of service. Purpose: verify coverage before service. (4) 271 - ELIGIBILITY, COVERAGE, OR BENEFIT INFORMATION RESPONSE - Response to 270 inquiry, provides: coverage status (active/inactive), plan information and coverage dates, copayment and deductible amounts, out-of-pocket maximums, covered/non-covered services, authorization requirements, coordination of benefits. Purpose: inform provider of patient coverage. Real-time: 10-30 second response typical. Replaces: phone calls to insurance. CLAIM STATUS TRANSACTIONS - (5) 276 - CLAIM STATUS REQUEST - Inquiry about submitted claim, includes: claim identifying information (claim number, patient, dates), provider information, payer information. Purpose: where is my claim, has it been paid? (6) 277 - CLAIM STATUS RESPONSE - Response to 276 inquiry, provides: claim receipt status, processing status (received, in process, finalized), payment status (paid, denied, pending), denial reason if applicable, estimated processing time, payer claim number. Purpose: track claim through payment. Replaces: phone calls for claim status. AUTHORIZATION TRANSACTIONS - (7) 278 - HEALTH CARE SERVICES REVIEW INFORMATION - Prior authorization request and response, request includes: patient information, requested service details, diagnosis and medical necessity, provider information, requested dates of service. Response includes: authorization approved/denied, authorization number if approved, approved dates and units, denial reason if denied. Purpose: obtain authorization before service. Adoption: less common than other transactions, many payers still use portal/phone/fax. ACKNOWLEDGMENT TRANSACTIONS - (8) 997 - FUNCTIONAL ACKNOWLEDGMENT - Technical receipt confirmation, validates: transaction received, syntax correct, required segments present, no transmission errors, provides: transaction control number, acceptance or rejection status, error details if rejected. Purpose: confirm transmission successful. Not claim adjudication: technical validation only. (9) 999 - IMPLEMENTATION ACKNOWLEDGMENT - Enhanced version of 997, more detailed error reporting, context-specific error identification, used for 5010 version transactions. Purpose: detailed transmission validation. ENROLLMENT TRANSACTIONS - (10) 834 - BENEFIT ENROLLMENT AND MAINTENANCE - Employee enrollment in health plan, includes: subscriber demographic information, coverage effective dates, plan selection, dependent information, change reasons (new hire, termination, change). Purpose: enroll employees in insurance. Primary use: employers to health plans. Less common in provider workflow. (11) 820 - PAYROLL DEDUCTED AND OTHER GROUP PREMIUM PAYMENT - Premium payment information, payment amounts and application, group and member details. Purpose: transmit premium payments. Use: employers to health plans. Not typically used by providers. TRANSACTION FREQUENCY - Daily/Real-time: 837 claims, 270/271 eligibility, 276/277 claim status. Weekly/Batch: 835 remittance (per payment cycle). As needed: 278 authorization, 997/999 acknowledgments. Monthly: 834 enrollment, 820 premium. TRANSACTION FORMAT - All use ANSI X12 standard structure: ISA/GS - Interchange and group headers, ST - Transaction set header, Transaction-specific segments (claim details, payment details, etc.), SE - Transaction set trailer, GE/IEA - Group and interchange trailers. Hierarchical structure with loops and segments. HIPAA REQUIREMENTS - Standard formats mandated by HIPAA, specific versions required (currently 5010), payers must accept: 837 claims, 270 eligibility inquiries, 276 claim status inquiries. Payers must send: 835 remittances (if electronic requested), 271 eligibility responses, 277 claim status responses. VERSION UPDATES - Industry transitions periodically (4010 → 5010 → future 7030), updates add fields and improve specificity, mandated transition dates, all covered entities must update.',
'EDI transaction types: CLAIMS: 837 (claims - 837P professional, 837I institutional, 837D dental, replaces CMS-1500/UB-04). PAYMENT: 835 (remittance advice, payment amounts/adjustments/denials, replaces paper EOB). ELIGIBILITY: 270 (inquiry), 271 (response, real-time 10-30 sec, replaces phone calls). CLAIM STATUS: 276 (inquiry), 277 (response, tracks claims). AUTHORIZATION: 278 (prior auth request/response, less common). ACKNOWLEDGMENT: 997/999 (receipt confirmation, technical validation). ENROLLMENT: 834 (benefit enrollment), 820 (premium payment). Frequency: daily (claims, eligibility, status), weekly (remittance), as needed (auth). HIPAA mandates standard formats (currently 5010 version).',
